@article{pennino_comparing_nodate,
	abstract = {A diversity of methodological approaches has been used in ecology to generate species distribution models (SDMs) and their amount has increased significantly during the last decades. Several studies have compared the performance of some of these techniques, offering relevant information on their use. These studies, however, have been mainly focused on terrestrial species, while marine ones have been less studied and fishery-dependent data from commercial fleet have been scarcely used. Here, we evaluate three different techniques of SDMs, such as hierarchical Bayesian spatial models, classification trees globally optimized with evolutionary algorithms and random forests, dealing with fishery-dependent data of two elasmobranch species. Most of the elasmobranchs are vulnerable species, more likely to be affected by intense fishing activity than most teleosts and for these reasons are considered a priority in fishery research and management. We discuss difference in the implemented approaches and the possible implication for the fishery management.},
